Q34. What should you be aware of when using someone else's virtual machine?
Ans:

Q35. What are some different ways to configure the networking between VMs?
Ans:  Every single virtual machine has its own network configuration The hypervisor can determine how that virtual machine is able to communicate.
 One configuration is by  choosing a shared network address, where the virtual machine has exactly the same IP address as the physical host that it’s running on. The virtual machine itself would be using a private IP address and then it would be using network address translation to be able to communicate using the IP address of the hypervisor.
 Another and a  more traditional networking configuration would be a bridged network address, where every VM has its own IP address.


Q36. What type of IP address does a virtual machine use?
Ans: Unique ip address

Q37. How does a virtual machine obtain an IP address?
Ans: When you start up a virtual machine, it goes through exactly the same process for obtaining an IP address as any physical device that’s connected to the network.

Q38. How can you lock down a VM so there is no communication outside of the local virtualized environment?
Ans: By configuring a private ip address.  In which case, it receiving an address on the network or not performing network address translation. Instead, that virtual machine is not able to communicate outside of the virtual network used amongst all of the other VMs.
